{"branch":"feat/p5-example-2","confidence":95,"prompt":"We just made a sketch that uses particles. It was inspired by an existing processing sketch and worked well.

Take a look at this sketch please. https://openprocessing.org/sketch/627398. There's a link (top-middle) to view the code. If you can't see the code, let me know and I'll copy it.

Have a look over the code and tell me whether we have enough API in medli to recreate it. If not, please let me know what we are missing"}

{"branch":"feat/p5-example-2","confidence":80,"prompt":"I'd like to see how our two p5.js ports work, with the SVG rendering. I'm sure there may be some problems, but it would be good to understand the limitations. So I'd like a flexible way to experiment with the full-screen demos. Maybe a '/svg/' page and a 'canvas' page, with query params to determine the sketch to load? Or a single '/full-screen' page with query params for both the sketch and the renderer choice.

Because the interactions are different for each of the two sketches, we need to account for that also. Perhaps each sketch also comes with a named function that's given the hammer.js manager for the canvas/svg element - and attaches whatever event handlers it needs. Then on page load we find the correct file, then use the well-named sketch and interaction handler functions.

What do you think? Capture the goal, then task an agent to investigate whether this is feasable and propose a design"}

{"branch":"feat/server","confidence":80,"prompt":"I want to put the viewport and interaction concerns to one side for the moment. I need to sleep on them, understand what's important and what this library should be opinionated about. Perhaps record that observation about both things.

Instead I want to have some more fun. Our Frame spec IR is serialisable. So in principle frame specs can be generated and updated anywhere, for instance... on a server! So, let's discuss the scope and options here. I want something simple that exercises serialisation. We will likely need a new generator - one that's able to fetch (or receive) from a remote source and simply provide what it's been given. And we will need some sort of headless setup with a generator that's updating frame specs for our consumer in the browser.

Websockets are an option, but will complicate the server for what is a simple demo. So a fetch is probably better. Let's keep it simple."}

{"branch":"feat/render-context","confidence":90,"prompt":"Can you upgrade the generate-pendulum.ts script so that it accepts optional query params? For targetWidth and targetHeight. **IF THEY ARE BOTH PRESENT**, the it can adapt the viewport sent with the frame. Half height should remain the same but half width should be adapted to match the aaspect ratio.

You will need to add a method to modify the viewport of Scene.

Then, adapt the remote-fetch generator to keep these values up to date as sent during frame(), and send them with the request."}
